<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/james/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>James</em></a> by Percival Everett</strong><br />
<strong>(Random House)</strong></p>
<p>“…the horror gathers gently in <em>James</em>. First, Everett moves to reorient these characters in his own moral landscape … leans in hard on its thriller elements and gathers speed and terror like a swelling storm. Its conclusion is equally shocking and exhilarating … What’s most striking, ultimately, is the way <em>James</em> both honors and interrogates <em>Huck Finn</em>, along with the nation that reveres it.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">–Ron Charles (<a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/books/2024/03/08/percival-everett-james-huck-finn/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Washington Post</em></a>)</p>
