<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>WOMEN’S PRIZE FOR FICTION</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Awarded to a female author of any nationality for the best original full-length novel written in English and published in the UK.<br />
Prize Money: £30,000<br />
</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/brotherless-night/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="126551" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/schmidt_michael_credit_ben_schmidt_3b/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Schmidt_Michael_credit_Ben_Schmidt_3b.jpg" data-orig-size="216,198" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;Ben Schmidt&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;Copyright 2012 Ben Schmidt \/ Schmidt Media Ltd&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Schmidt_Michael_credit_Ben_Schmidt_3b" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Schmidt_Michael_credit_Ben_Schmidt_3b.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Schmidt_Michael_credit_Ben_Schmidt_3b.jpg" class="wp-image-126551 size-medium aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/01/Brotherless-Night-200x300.jpg" sizes="auto, (max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/01/Brotherless-Night-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/01/Brotherless-Night-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/01/Brotherless-Night.jpg 267w" alt="Brotherless Night" width="200" height="300" data-attachment-id="126551" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/5-reviews-you-need-to-read-this-week-1-5-2023/brotherless-night/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/01/Brotherless-Night.jpg" data-orig-size="267,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Brotherless Night" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/01/Brotherless-Night-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/01/Brotherless-Night.jpg" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/brotherless-night/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Brotherless Night</em></a> by V. V. Ganeshananthan</strong><br />
<strong>(Random House)</strong></p>
<p>“Devastating … Part of Ganeshananthan’s genius lies in the way she gives the reader a multifaceted perspective on Sashi’s motivations … A spectacular work of historical fiction: thoroughly researched, brimming with outrage and compassion, and full of indelible imagery.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">–Yagnishsing Dawoor (<a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/article/2024/may/03/brotherless-night-by-vv-ganeshananthan-review-heartbreak-in-war-torn-sri-lanka" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Guardian</em></a>)</p>
<p><strong>Finalists:</strong></p>
<p>Anne Enright, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/the-wren-the-wren/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Wren, the Wren</em></a> (W. W. Norton &amp; Company)<br />
Kate Grenville, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781805302483" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Restless Dolly Maunder</em></a> (Cannongate)<br />
Isabella Hammad, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/enter-ghost/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Enter Ghost</em></a> (Grove)<br />
Claire Kilroy, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/soldier-sailor/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Soldier Sailor</em></a> (Scribner)<br />
Aube Rey Lescure, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/river-east-river-west/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>River East, River West</em></a> (William Morrow &amp; Company)</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>PEN/</strong><b>FAULKNER AWARD</b></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Awarded to the author of the year’s best work of fiction by a living American citizen.</em><br />
<em>Prize money: $15,000</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/what-happened-to-ruthy-ramirez/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-132341 size-medium aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/12/What-Happened-to-Ruthy-Ramirez-199x300.jpg" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/12/What-Happened-to-Ruthy-Ramirez-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/12/What-Happened-to-Ruthy-Ramirez-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/12/What-Happened-to-Ruthy-Ramirez.jpg 265w" alt="What Happened to Ruthy Ramirez" width="199" height="300" data-attachment-id="132341" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/?attachment_id=132341" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/12/What-Happened-to-Ruthy-Ramirez.jpg" data-orig-size="265,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="What Happened to Ruthy Ramirez" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/12/What-Happened-to-Ruthy-Ramirez-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/12/What-Happened-to-Ruthy-Ramirez.jpg" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/what-happened-to-ruthy-ramirez/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>What Happened to Ruthy Ramirez</em></a> by Claire Jiménez</strong><br />
<strong>(Grand Central Publishing)</strong></p>
<p>“There’s a delightfully subversive and maverick quality to the way first-time novelist Jiménez gives her characters the freedom to tell the truth as they see it … Jiménez brings bravery to the page, and it’s her strong storytelling and humor that make this an outstanding debut.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><a href="https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/claire-jimenez/what-happened-ruthy-ramirez/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>–Kirkus</em></a></p>
<p><strong>Finalists:</strong></p>
<p>Jamel Brinkley, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/witness-stories/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Witness</em></a> (Farrar, Straus and Giroux)<br />
Henry Hoke, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/open-throat/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Open Throat</em></a> (MCD)<br />
Alice McDermott, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/absolution/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Absolution</em></a> (Farrar, Straus and Giroux)<br />
Colin Winnette, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/users/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Users</em></a> (Soft Skull)</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div class="code-block code-block-9">
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>ANDREW CARNEGIE MEDAL FOR EXCELLENCE IN FICTION</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Awards established in 2012 to recognize the best fiction and nonfiction books for adult readers published in the U.S. in the previous year. Administered by the American Library Association.</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Prize money: $5,000 (winner), $1,500 (finalists)</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/the-berry-pickers/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="129774" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-art-of-war-is-actually-a-manual-on-how-to-avoid-it/korean_war_bombing_wonsan/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Korean_War_bombing_Wonsan.jpg" data-orig-size="798,401" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Korean_War_bombing_Wonsan" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Korean_War_bombing_Wonsan-300x151.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Korean_War_bombing_Wonsan.jpg" class="wp-image-129774 size-medium aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/10/dbe32cfd833aab0772713ad4b5f2f0b6-200x300.gif" sizes="auto, (max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/10/dbe32cfd833aab0772713ad4b5f2f0b6-200x300.gif 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/10/dbe32cfd833aab0772713ad4b5f2f0b6-33x50.gif 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/10/dbe32cfd833aab0772713ad4b5f2f0b6.gif 432w" alt="Amanda Peters_The Berry Pickers Cover" width="200" height="300" data-attachment-id="129774" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/bookmark/the-berry-pickers/the-berry-pickers-cover/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/10/dbe32cfd833aab0772713ad4b5f2f0b6.gif" data-orig-size="432,648" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Amanda Peters_The Berry Pickers Cover" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/10/dbe32cfd833aab0772713ad4b5f2f0b6-200x300.gif" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/10/dbe32cfd833aab0772713ad4b5f2f0b6.gif" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/the-berry-pickers/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Berry Pickers</em></a> by Amanda Peters</strong><br />
<strong>(Catapult)</strong></p>
<p>“Not meant to be a mystery. The strength of Amanda Peters’s novel lies in its understanding of how trauma spreads through a life and a family, and its depiction of the challenges facing Indigenous people … Though the plot is overdetermined and overly drawn out, nuanced characterizations benefit from all the space they have to develop.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">–Marion Winik (<a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/books/2023/11/19/berry-pickers-amanda-peters-review/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Washington Post</em></a>)</p>
<p><strong>Finalists:</strong></p>
<p>Christina Wong and Daniel Innes, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781770417151" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Denison Avenue</em></a> (ECW Press)<br />
Jesmyn Ward, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/let-us-descend/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Let Us Descend</em></a> (Scribner)</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>INTERNATIONAL DUBLIN LITERARY AWARD</strong></p>
<div class="code-block code-block-9">
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>An international literary award presented each year for a novel written in English or translated into English.</em><br />
<em>Prize money: €100,000</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781646052028" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="129966" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2020/lawrence-joseph-author-pic/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Lawrence-Joseph-Author-Pic.jpg" data-orig-size="904,1275" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;4&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;Canon EOS 5D Mark III&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1486341636&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;85&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;160&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.00625&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Lawrence Joseph Author Pic" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Lawrence-Joseph-Author-Pic-213x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Lawrence-Joseph-Author-Pic-726x1024.jpg" class="wp-image-129966 size-medium aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/12/Solenoid-211x300.png" sizes="auto, (max-width: 211px) 100vw, 211px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/12/Solenoid-211x300.png 211w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/12/Solenoid-720x1024.png 720w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/12/Solenoid-768x1092.png 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/12/Solenoid-35x50.png 35w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/12/Solenoid.png 1020w" alt="Solenoid" width="211" height="300" data-attachment-id="129966" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/the-award-winning-novels-of-2023/solenoid/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/12/Solenoid.png" data-orig-size="1020,1450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Solenoid" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/12/Solenoid-211x300.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/12/Solenoid-720x1024.png" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781646052028" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Solenoid</em></a> by Mircea Cărtărescu, tr. by Sean Cotter</strong><br />
<strong>(Deep Vellum)</strong></p>
<p>“[S]omething of a masterpiece … Solenoid synthesizes and subtly mocks elements of autofiction and history fiction by way of science fiction. The result is unlike any genre in ambition or effect, something else altogether, a self-sufficient style that proudly rejects its less emancipated alternatives…The mesmerizing beauty of creation, of reality giving way to itself: that, above all, lies behind the doors of Solenoid.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">–Federico Perelmuter (<a href="https://astra-mag.com/articles/this-invented-nation/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Astra</em></a>)</p>
<p><strong>Finalists:</strong></p>
<p>Sebastian Barry, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/old-gods-time/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Old God’s Time</em></a> (Viking)<br />
Emma Donoghue, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/haven/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Haven</em></a> (Little Brown and Company)<br />
Jonathan Escoffery, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/all/if-i-survive-you/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>If I Survive You</em></a> (MCD)<br />
Suzette Mayr, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781552454589" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Sleeping Car Porter</em></a> (Coach House Books)<br />
Alexis Wright, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/praiseworthy/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Praiseworthy</em></a> (New Directions)</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>CENTER FOR FICTION FIRST NOVEL PRIZE</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>An annual award presented by The Center for Fiction, a non-profit organization in New York City, for the best debut novel.</em><br />
<em>Prize money: $10,000</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="131363" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/failsafe-reading-recommendations-for-your-non-reader-friend-in-need/9-therapy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/9-therapy.jpg" data-orig-size="300,362" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="9 therapy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/9-therapy-249x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/9-therapy.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-131363 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/06/b12c4b16c48668f6d4ff6630e1d72e57-201x300.gif" sizes="auto, (max-width: 201px) 100vw, 201px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/06/b12c4b16c48668f6d4ff6630e1d72e57-201x300.gif 201w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/06/b12c4b16c48668f6d4ff6630e1d72e57-34x50.gif 34w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/06/b12c4b16c48668f6d4ff6630e1d72e57.gif 435w" alt="God Bless You, Otis Spunkmeyer Cover" width="201" height="300" data-attachment-id="131363" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/bookmark/god-bless-you-otis-spunkmeyer/god-bless-you-otis-spunkmeyer-cover/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/06/b12c4b16c48668f6d4ff6630e1d72e57.gif" data-orig-size="435,648" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="God Bless You, Otis Spunkmeyer Cover" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/06/b12c4b16c48668f6d4ff6630e1d72e57-201x300.gif" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/06/b12c4b16c48668f6d4ff6630e1d72e57.gif" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/god-bless-you-otis-spunkmeyer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>God Bless You, Otis Spunkmeyer</em></a> by Joesph Earl Thomas</strong><br />
<strong>(Grand Central)</strong></p>
<p>“I was poring over prose unlike anything I’d previously encountered, prose that felt at times unruly but always athletic in its meta pursuit of clarity … This is a book that’s not afraid of a tangent. It’s a risky quality, one that may prompt some readers to dismiss <em>Otis Spunkmeyer</em> as rambly, as I did at first. But there is a great deal of genius in the novel’s sprawl … Thomas loads his sentences and scenes with so much detail that up close they may feel abstruse, at least initially. But like the work of Jackson Pollock, the novel reveals itself the longer one spends time with it. Keep looking, the chaos will start to show its pattern, its rhythm, its dimension and its awe-inspiring color.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">–Danez Smith (<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2024/06/17/books/review/god-bless-you-otis-spunkmeyer-joseph-earl-thomas.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The New York Times Book Review</em></a>)</p>
<p><strong>Finalists:</strong></p>
<p>Rita Bullwinkel, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/headshot/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Headshot</em></a> (Viking)<br />
Ruthvika Rao, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781250899903" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Fertile Earth</em></a> (Flatiron)<br />
Mai Sennaar, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/they-dream-in-gold/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>They Dream in Gold</em></a> (Zando)<br />
Clare Sestanovich, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/ask-me-again/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Ask Me Again</em></a> (Knopf)<br />
Morgan Talty, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/fire-exit/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Fire Exit</em></a> (Tin House Books)<br />
Ledia Xhoga, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781959030805" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Misinterpretation</em></a> (Tin House Books)</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><b><i>LOS ANGELES TIMES </i>BOOK PRIZE</b></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Recognizes outstanding literary works as well as champions new writers.<br />
</em><em>Prize money: $1,000</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>(ART SEIDENBAUM AWARD FOR FIRST FICTION)</strong></p>
<p><a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/company-stories/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="129753" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2020/how-much-of-these-hills-is-gold-1/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/how-much-of-these-hills-is-gold-1.jpg" data-orig-size="1200,1812" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="C Pam Zhang, How Much of These Hills Is Gold" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/how-much-of-these-hills-is-gold-1-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/how-much-of-these-hills-is-gold-1-678x1024.jpg" class="wp-image-129753 size-medium aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/10/77e512f0544b7bb9b181377a7cb6844e-200x300.gif" sizes="auto, (max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/10/77e512f0544b7bb9b181377a7cb6844e-200x300.gif 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/10/77e512f0544b7bb9b181377a7cb6844e-33x50.gif 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/10/77e512f0544b7bb9b181377a7cb6844e.gif 432w" alt="Shannon Sanders_Company: Stories Cover" width="200" height="300" data-attachment-id="129753" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/bookmark/company-stories/company-stories-cover/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/10/77e512f0544b7bb9b181377a7cb6844e.gif" data-orig-size="432,648" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Shannon Sanders_Company: Stories Cover" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/10/77e512f0544b7bb9b181377a7cb6844e-200x300.gif" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/10/77e512f0544b7bb9b181377a7cb6844e.gif" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/company-stories/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Company: Stories</em></a> by Shannon Sanders</strong><br />
<strong>(Graywolf)</strong></p>
<p>“One of the great pleasures of <em>Company</em>—and there are many—is how some stories double back to retell an event or re-establish a family member from a different vantage point, deepening our understanding of, and investment in, the Collinses … This is a collection that builds intrigue through both what we see and what we don’t see. As we jump from story to story, between different times and different perspectives, it’s thrilling to re-encounter past characters in new circumstances and speculate about how we got here … A deftly woven tapestry that scrupulously depicts familial ties and estrangement, richly told with a nuance that allows each character dignity and grace.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">–Jonathan Escoffery (<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/10/22/books/review/this-is-salvaged-company-holler-child-vauhini-vara-shannon-sanders-latoya-watkins.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The New York Times Book Review</em></a>)</p>
<p><strong>Finalists:</strong></p>
<p>Stephen Buoro, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781635577778" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Five Sorrowful Mysteries of Andy Africa</em></a> (Bloomsbury)<br />
Sheena Patel, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/im-a-fan/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>I’m a Fan</em></a> (Graywolf)<br />
James Frankie Thomas, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/idlewild/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Idlewild</em></a> (Overlook Press)<br />
Ghassan Zeineddine, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/dearborn/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Dearborn</em></a> (Tin House Books)</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>(FICTION)</strong></p>
<p><a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/same-bed-different-dreams/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="129800" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/after-months-of-controversy-the-romance-writers-of-americas-leaders-have-resigned/43-434407_fire-hearts-heart-on-fire-png/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/43-434407_fire-hearts-heart-on-fire-png.jpg" data-orig-size="800,443" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="43-434407_fire-hearts-heart-on-fire-png" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/43-434407_fire-hearts-heart-on-fire-png-300x166.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/43-434407_fire-hearts-heart-on-fire-png.jpg" class="wp-image-129800 size-medium aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/11/a08b31c9dcca10a25d3d924ba1cd0989-197x300.gif" sizes="auto, (max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/11/a08b31c9dcca10a25d3d924ba1cd0989-197x300.gif 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/11/a08b31c9dcca10a25d3d924ba1cd0989-33x50.gif 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/11/a08b31c9dcca10a25d3d924ba1cd0989.gif 426w" alt="Ed Park_Same Bed Different Dreams Cover" width="197" height="300" data-attachment-id="129800" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/bookmark/same-bed-different-dreams/same-bed-different-dreams-cover/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/11/a08b31c9dcca10a25d3d924ba1cd0989.gif" data-orig-size="426,648" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Ed Park_Same Bed Different Dreams Cover" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/11/a08b31c9dcca10a25d3d924ba1cd0989-197x300.gif" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/11/a08b31c9dcca10a25d3d924ba1cd0989.gif" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/same-bed-different-dreams/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Same Bed Different Dreams</em></a> by Ed Park</strong><br />
<strong>(Random House)</strong></p>
<p>“It’s a challenging read and yet wonderfully suspenseful, like watching a circus performer juggle a dozen torches; will one slip his agile hands? Park seeks to encompass the vast Korean diaspora, but he’s also fleeing realism, a personal diaspora, away from conventional forms … <em>Same Bed Different Dreams</em> struts confidently across registers—lyrical, deadpan, acerbic, comedic—while doling out clues. Characters rotate in and out, some glimpsed in passing, their motives opaque … Sprawling, stunning.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">–Hamilton Cain (<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/11/02/books/review/same-bed-different-dreams-ed-park.html#:~:text=%E2%80%9CSame%20Bed%20Different%20Dreams%E2%80%9D%20demands,one%20slip%20his%20agile%20hands%3F" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The New York Times Book Review</em></a>)</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>EDGAR AWARD</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Presented by the Mystery Writers of America, honoring the best in crime and mystery fiction.</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780802163387" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="132342" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/relearning-to-write-after-law-school-buried-my-voice/legal-pads/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/legal-pads.jpg" data-orig-size="779,373" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="legal pads" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/legal-pads-300x144.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/legal-pads.jpg" class="wp-image-132342 size-medium aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/12/Flags-on-the-Bayou-199x300.jpg" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/12/Flags-on-the-Bayou-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/12/Flags-on-the-Bayou-678x1024.jpg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/12/Flags-on-the-Bayou-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/12/Flags-on-the-Bayou.jpg 700w" alt="Flags on the Bayou" width="199" height="300" data-attachment-id="132342" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/?attachment_id=132342" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/12/Flags-on-the-Bayou.jpg" data-orig-size="700,1057" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&q