<div class="code-block code-block-9">
<p style="text-align: center;"><b>BRAM STOKER AWARD</b></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Presented by the Horror Writers Association for “superior achievement” in horror writing for novels.</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/the-reformatory/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="129772" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-art-of-war-is-actually-a-manual-on-how-to-avoid-it/51kogb9kbpl-_sx306_bo1204203200_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/51KOgb9kbpL._SX306_BO1204203200_.jpg" data-orig-size="308,499" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="51KOgb9kbpL._SX306_BO1,204,203,200_" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/51KOgb9kbpL._SX306_BO1204203200_-185x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/51KOgb9kbpL._SX306_BO1204203200_.jpg" class="wp-image-129772 size-medium aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/10/e85485a55339608670db8b8195260ef6-199x300.gif" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/10/e85485a55339608670db8b8195260ef6-199x300.gif 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/10/e85485a55339608670db8b8195260ef6-33x50.gif 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/10/e85485a55339608670db8b8195260ef6.gif 429w" alt="Tananarive Due_The Reformatory Cover" width="199" height="300" data-attachment-id="129772" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/bookmark/the-reformatory/the-reformatory-cover/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/10/e85485a55339608670db8b8195260ef6.gif" data-orig-size="429,648" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Tananarive Due_The Reformatory Cover" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/10/e85485a55339608670db8b8195260ef6-199x300.gif" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2023/10/e85485a55339608670db8b8195260ef6.gif" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/the-reformatory/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Reformatory</em></a> by Tananarive Due</strong><br />
<strong>(Gallery / Saga)</strong></p>
<p>“Emotive and eschews realism for the supernatural. It combines current concerns about race and justice for young Black men with an intensely readable, immersive story with decisive paranormal features. In fact, the novel’s extended, layered denouement is so heart-smashingly good, it made me late for work. I couldn’t stop reading. I needed to find out what was going to happen next, and next, and next … A supernatural historical novel and a straight-up page-turner. This is a difficult combination to sustain for nearly 600 pages, but Due accomplishes it, and in so doing invites us to consider what it means to be enthralled, even entertained, by a young man’s ethical dilemmas, and to find ourselves unexpectedly rooting for revenge, for the living and the dead.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">–Randy Boyagoda (<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/10/27/books/review/the-reformatory-tananarive-due.html#:~:text=It%20combines%20current%20concerns%20about,I%20couldn\\\\\\\'t%20stop%20reading." target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The New York Times Book Review</em></a>)</p>
</div>
<p><strong>Finalists:</strong></p>
<p>Grady Hendrix, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/how-to-sell-a-haunted-house/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>How To Sell A Haunted House</em></a> (Berkley)<br />
Stephen Graham Jones, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/dont-fear-the-reaper/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Don’t Fear the Reaper</em></a> (Gallery / Saga)<br />
Victor Lavalle, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/lone-women/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Lone Women</em></a> (One World)<br />
Chuck Tingle, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781250874634" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Camp Damascus</em></a> (Tor Nightfire)<br />
Chuck Wendig, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780593158760" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Black River Orchard</em></a> (Del Rey)</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>GILLER PRIZE</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Given to a Canadian author of a novel or short story collection published in English (including translation) the previous year.<br />
Prize Money: $100,000 (winner), $10,000 (finalists)<br />
</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="size-medium wp-image-130155 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/01/69a44b3907bc9936e7277c6b26850c7e-205x300.gif" sizes="auto, (max-width: 205px) 100vw, 205px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/01/69a44b3907bc9936e7277c6b26850c7e-205x300.gif 205w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/01/69a44b3907bc9936e7277c6b26850c7e-34x50.gif 34w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/01/69a44b3907bc9936e7277c6b26850c7e.gif 442w" alt="Anne Michaels_Held Cover" width="205" height="300" data-attachment-id="130155" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/bookmark/held/held-cover/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/01/69a44b3907bc9936e7277c6b26850c7e.gif" data-orig-size="442,648" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Anne Michaels_Held Cover" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/01/69a44b3907bc9936e7277c6b26850c7e-205x300.gif" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/01/69a44b3907bc9936e7277c6b26850c7e.gif" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/held/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Held</em></a> by Anne Michaels</strong><br />
<strong>(Knopf)</strong></p>
<p>“Michaels is a Canadian poet, essayist and fiction writer, and her radiant novel harnesses this doubleness, finding points of contact between the physical world of mortality and the abstract realm of remembrance … Her imagery shimmers with metaphoric significance … Strange, lovely.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">–Sam Sacks (<a href="https://www.wsj.com/arts-culture/books/fiction-held-by-anne-michaels-76a71ea5" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Wall Street Journal</em></a>)</p>
<p><strong>Finalists:</strong></p>
<p>Éric Chacour (tr. Pablo Strauss), <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781552454855" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>What I Know About You</em></a> (Coach House Books)<br />
Anne Fleming, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781039004993" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Curiosities</em></a> (Vintage Books Canada)<br />
Conor Kerr, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781517917234" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Prairie Edge</em></a> (University of Minnesota Press)<br />
Deepa Rajagopalan, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781487012403" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Peacocks of Instagram</em></a> (Astoria)</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</p></span>
									
																		
